The reasons for such optimism, among others, and pessimism, among others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data is the fingerprints, the hand contour and the poisonous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very weak fingers and their prints are inseparable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identification field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the poison network and the contour of the hand imply a voluntary and precise gesture of people.
It is both a security - we cannot capture this data in themselves - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore take time.
As a result, research has been carried out for twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of sensors and the computer calculation capacity necessary for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The precision of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of the Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridar Iyengar, Director of Intel Labs Security Research.
A unique and infallible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirmed Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Perspective to CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a suitcase costing EUR 90,000 to analyse DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
The use of biometrics is divided into two groups: identification (recognise one person among others) and authentication (to ensure that the person is the person who claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already set.
This allows to ensure that one person does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We will recover the images of surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, who, at NEC France, is responsible for commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a photo of a kid making the queue in a store, follow his progress thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (frontiers, protected premises, canteens...) or logical (opening of a computer).
More recently, the presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a friend who points for another," says Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by entering his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and large distribution teachers: when paying in store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometric seductive in the eyes of the general public.
The first is to explain that she can make time.
"If, thanks to biometry, a customer remains in the box for 30 seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, restorate by putting forward the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Digital prints are stored on a first server; the identity of the persons is in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which blocks itself if we try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
However, in the absence of detailed studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy professionals, they, continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the enormous amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me afraid of the worst: generalized surveillance," predicts Andrew Patrick, Canada's Privacy Commissioner.
