Scientists have just shed light on how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies revealed that happy dogs removed their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs removed it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved in different ways in incentives that generate positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs' disordered tail movements, researchers have followed animals as they watched films containing other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs of the films of other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other factor of confusion – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression remove the tail to the right (from the dog's point of view who removes the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail turn mainly to the left (once again from the dog's point of view that removes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other because of these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet several times in other dogs and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail towards one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will respond to this experience."
Researchers indicate that results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The canine behavioral expert John Bradshaw, a professor invited to the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, stated that it was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their head to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when his tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He pointed out that the differences could be due to the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or dogs robots as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, identified in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs do not make an exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
