A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York identified a new species of forest dolphin outside northern Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for scientific mission to the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) comes to the Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new dolphin species surprise you?
It's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
If, in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
Furthermore, it is not possible that such advances in genetics and molecular biology would cause a species to be classified or belonging to a species, a family, or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on the morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are being called into question because of the progress of genetics.
Similarly, two very close species were morphologically distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific pine dolphins and the Atlantic pine whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known by researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present in this area.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could have a case of extinction of a species, rather than of a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered to be threatened or extinct according to the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. stock, and the possibility to be restored from neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new discovered species has grown, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located on top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, where there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This bridging of genes limits the creation of new species.
On the contrary, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It must be known that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
