"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We'd have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to hospitals and hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could benefit from.
"It's not easy," adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5:00, go to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they've been waiting too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor for 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three quarters of the country's health expenditure is carried out in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," said Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed more than 700 surgical acts free of charge last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital of Yaoundé.
And it has created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which goes into rural areas during the weekend to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Nearly every Friday, with 30 people, they settle in vans after fixing the medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to go to villages that need the most help.
The chance doesn't always follow them.
They have often had to push vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received in heroes: the community organizes a party, singing and dancing and offers them the best accommodations available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and energy flowing – is more than happy to join the parties.
The next morning, the team starts receiving hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people every visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
Sometimes they live 60 km from the village, and they walk.
In this travelling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people are treated with malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can receive bees, a pair of bees collected or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the practical team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, a mayor or a house; after the intervention, the patient wakes up and goes to the wake room to leave his room for the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the electromagnetic group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers are working until the first hours of Sunday morning.
It's a steady pace, but village musicians generally help the team stay motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work," explained Mr. Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work it has done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year, and knows that their presence can make a difference for those to whom they come for help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to care for a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," said the man.
In addition to making this travelling hospital live and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works nighttime in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
This is the second job, he explains, which accounts for 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's asleep," said Katie O'Malley, a medical student in the second year of Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteering in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still at the hospital or trying to find money for his association so he can carry out these campaigns.
For medical students and nurses such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, it is an opportunity to learn on the ground that they do not have at their home.
"We were able to participate in operations to assist in the spraying of blood or to transfer the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
It's not something you have the chance to do in America when you're studying medicine in the second year.
Voluntary students generally pay for their journey to Cameroon, and often arrive with the medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"It's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonese people is not close to spreading.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a challenge.
Helping others to live happily by keeping his promise to his father is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," said Mr. Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieve the pain are the reasons that motivate me to do this.
